## Scope

This slice owns the inverse and synthesis half of the application: a library-agnostic optimization interface; the sole ALGLIB adapter behind it; the parameter⇄system design-variable mapping reusing `ArbitraryVariable.getSys`; the [Core] target/merit-function editor and local refinement (LM/quasi-Newton/Nelder–Mead); [Standard] Ψ/Δ ellipsometric residuals (sharing §F.5), inverse fitting from measured R/T and Ψ,Δ, fit-quality reporting, needle/tunnelling synthesis and global optimization; the Synthesis/Fit operator page with its UX checklist; and the Wolfram reference-fit validation tests. ALGLIB is used for optimization ONLY and never touches engine linear algebra (which stays on the Part A math seam). All canonical-units, JSON-canonical, `.binz`-derived, and tier-fidelity rules apply.

## Requirements

The following are the parent's Part G directives, reproduced verbatim. Contractful identifiers and `<file>:<line>` references are preserved exactly.

### R-1 (G.1) Library-agnostic optimization interface

This part MUST define the optimization abstraction in our own terms in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/OptimizationInterface.fs` inside the `OpticalConstructor.Optimization.fsproj` project named in the Part A assembly map. The interface MUST be expressed as F# records and discriminated unions (§0 constraint 1) and MUST NOT reference any ALGLIB type in its public surface, so the physics/fitting code compiles without the library, per §A.8 ("the physics/fitting code never depends on ALGLIB directly").

The interface MUST consist of exactly:
- `Residual = float[] -> float[]` — the vectorized residual function (one entry per target sample), matching §A.8's `(float[] -> float[])`.
- `Jacobian = (float[] -> float[][]) option` — optional analytic Jacobian; when `None` the adapter MUST request numerical differentiation.
- `ParameterBounds` (record: `lower : float[]`, `upper : float[]`) — per-parameter box bounds in canonical SI units (§0 constraint 3); an unbounded side MUST be encoded as `infinity`/`-infinity`.
- `InequalityTarget` (DU: `LessOrEqual | GreaterOrEqual` carrying the bound) — the one-sided target from 010 §II.5 ("R ≤ 0.5%").
- `OptimizationMethod` (DU: `LevenbergMarquardt | QuasiNewtonLbfgs | NelderMead | BoundedLinearConstrained | NonlinearConstrained`) — the method selector mapping onto the ALGLIB routines named in §A.8/010 §III.4: `LevenbergMarquardt → minlm`, `QuasiNewtonLbfgs → minlbfgs`, `BoundedLinearConstrained → minbleic`, `NonlinearConstrained → minnlc`. `NelderMead` is the 010-required simplex method (010 line 219) whose concrete backend 010 leaves unnamed; its routine binding is deferred per G.2 and MUST NOT be resolved to a spec-invented routine here.
- `OptimizationRequest` (record: residual, optional jacobian, initial `float[]`, bounds, inequality targets, method, `maxIterations : int`, `epsX : float`) — the single call payload.
- `OptimizationResult` (record: `solution : float[]`, `finalResiduals : float[]`, `iterations : int`, `terminationReason : TerminationReason`, `success : bool`) where `TerminationReason` is a DU (`Converged | MaxIterationsReached | StepTooSmall | Failed of string`).

The interface MUST expose a single entry point `optimize : OptimizationRequest -> Result<OptimizationResult, string>` (§0 error-handling rule: `Result`, not exceptions). No caching, retry, or progress-callback registry is admitted in this file; progress reporting is wired in G.10 via a separate channel.

### R-2 (G.2) ALGLIB adapter behind the interface

This part MUST implement the interface from G.1 in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/AlglibAdapter.fs`, the ONLY file in the solution permitted to `open`/reference ALGLIB. ALGLIB MUST be added as a NuGet `PackageReference` to `OpticalConstructor.Optimization.fsproj` (no new C# project — §0 constraint 1); the GPL free edition is the licensed edition per §A.8.

The adapter MUST map each `OptimizationMethod` to the ALGLIB routine named in §A.8: `LevenbergMarquardt → minlm` (`minlmcreatev`/`minlmcreatevj` when a Jacobian is supplied, with `minlmsetbc` for bounds), `QuasiNewtonLbfgs → minlbfgs`, `BoundedLinearConstrained → minbleic`, `NonlinearConstrained → minnlc`. `NelderMead` is the [Standard] Nelder–Mead simplex method 010 §II.5 requires (010 line 219), but 010 §III.4 names NO ALGLIB routine for a simplex solver — its list is exactly `minlm`/`minbleic`/`minnlc`/`minlbfgs`/`mincg`/`lsfit` (010 lines 380-382). This part MUST NOT invent an ALGLIB routine name for the simplex case; the following deferred decision is carried forward VERBATIM as a directive: **the concrete simplex backend for `NelderMead` — an ALGLIB routine if one is later confirmed to exist, OR an explicit in-file F# Nelder–Mead loop over the G.1 `Residual` closure — is deliberately undecided here and MUST remain undecided until that decision is taken, traceable to the 010-required simplex feature; this part MUST NOT resolve it by binding `NelderMead` to a spec-invented ALGLIB routine.** Until that decision is taken the adapter MUST surface `NelderMead` as `Failed "simplex backend unresolved"` rather than silently dispatching to a guessed routine. The adapter MUST translate `ParameterBounds` into the routine's box-constraint call and `InequalityTarget`s into either residual penalty rows (for `minlm`) or nonlinear constraints (for `minnlc`); it MUST convert ALGLIB's completion codes into `TerminationReason` and MUST NOT leak an ALGLIB exception past the `Result` boundary. Linear algebra inside the adapter (normal-equation/QR solves for the LM step) is ALGLIB's own; this part MUST NOT route any matrix operation through `MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5`, and conversely MUST NOT use ALGLIB for any engine linear algebra (§A.8: "ALGLIB is used for optimization only, not for linear algebra"). Extreme Optimization MUST NOT be referenced from this adapter; `ExtremeNumericsMath.fs:5` remains a legacy math-seam reference only, per §A.8.

### R-3 (G.3) Parameter ⇄ system mapping (design variables)

This part MUST define the bridge from a flat `float[]` parameter vector to a concrete `OpticalSystem` in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/DesignParameters.fs`, reusing the existing scalar parametrization seam `ArbitraryVariable.getSys : OpticalSystem -> double -> OpticalSystem` (`Variables.fs:37`) that `calculate` already calls at `Variables.fs:263`. A `DesignParameter` (new record) MUST carry a `name : string`, a `getSys : OpticalSystem -> double -> OpticalSystem` closure (the same signature as `ArbitraryVariable.getSys`), and the per-parameter SI bound pair; an ordered `DesignParameter list` MUST fold left over a base `OpticalSystem` to apply the whole `float[]` vector, in vector order.

The supported design variables MUST be: **layer thickness** — the closure MUST rebuild the target `Layer` with `Thickness (v * 1.0<meter>)` (`Media.fs:12`), v already in canonical meters (§0 constraint 3); **dispersion coefficient** — the closure MUST substitute into the relevant `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53`) field; **wedge angle** — the closure MUST set the `WedgeLayer.angle` (`Media.fs:34`). Negative-thickness prohibition and physical n-range bounding (010 §II.5) MUST be expressed as the `ParameterBounds` of G.1 (lower bound 0 for thickness), NOT as a separate validator. This file MUST NOT introduce reflection-based field setting; every mapping is an explicit F# closure the reader can follow (§0 locality rule).

### R-4 (G.4) Target / merit-function editor [Core]

This part MUST define the merit/target model in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/MeritFunction.fs` and surface it in the UI per G.10, carrying the **[Core]** tier from 010 §II.5. A `FitTarget` (new record) MUST carry: the `OpticalFunction` to evaluate (reuse `FieldFunctions.fs:109`: `R | Rp | Rs | T | Tp | Ts | EllipticityR | …`, extended for Ψ/Δ per G.6), the independent-variable sample point (a `RangedVariable` index or explicit `WaveLength`/`IncidenceAngle`, reusing `Variables.fs:42`), the desired value, a `weight : float`, a `tolerance : float`, and a `kind : TargetKind` DU (`Equality | Inequality of InequalityTarget`) — covering 010 §II.5's "weights, tolerances, and one-sided/inequality targets".

The merit function MUST be assembled as a weighted least-squares residual vector: for each `FitTarget`, residual = weight × (modelValue − desiredValue) / max(tolerance, ε) for `Equality`, and a one-sided hinge (zero when satisfied) for `Inequality`. `modelValue` MUST be obtained by running `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) on the system produced by the G.3 mapping at the target's sample point and reading `Solution.func` (`FieldFunctions.fs:192`) — the SAME evaluator the charts use, so fit and chart never diverge. The assembled residual closure MUST satisfy the `Residual` signature of G.1 directly. Stored `desiredValue`/sample points MUST be canonical SI (meters for wavelength via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`); unit conversion happens only at the editor boundary (§0 constraint 3). No merit-evaluation cache is admitted here.

### R-5 (G.5) Local refinement optimization [Core]

This part MUST implement local refinement in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/LocalRefinement.fs`, carrying the **[Core]** tier from 010 §II.5. The entry point MUST take a base `OpticalSystem`, a `DesignParameter list` (G.3), a `FitTarget list` (G.4), and an `OptimizationMethod` (G.1), build the residual closure, and call `optimize` (G.1). Levenberg–Marquardt (`LevenbergMarquardt`) MUST be the default method ("the workhorse", 010 §II.5); quasi-Newton (`QuasiNewtonLbfgs`) and Nelder–Mead simplex (`NelderMead`) MUST be selectable. Bounded parameters MUST be honoured by passing the G.3 bounds as `ParameterBounds`, and inequality targets MUST flow through as G.1 `InequalityTarget`s — satisfying 010 §II.5's "bounded parameters and inequality targets (forbid negative thickness, bound n to physical ranges)".

On success the optimizer's `solution` vector MUST be folded back through the G.3 mapping to produce the refined `OpticalSystem`, which becomes the new working system. Robust normal-equation handling (QR / Gauss–Jordan, 010 §II.5) is delegated to ALGLIB's `minlm` internals via G.2 and MUST NOT be re-implemented on the math seam. This file MUST NOT spawn its own thread; long-running execution and cancellation are owned by G.10.

### R-6 (G.6) Ψ, Δ derivation for ellipsometric residuals [Standard]

This part MUST add the ellipsometric quantities Ψ and Δ as evaluable optimization targets in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/Ellipsometry.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 §II.4 ("Ψ, Δ … derivable from existing field amplitudes"). The derivation MUST reuse the complex reflected `EmComponent` amplitudes already solved by `getRT` (`Solvers.fs:74`) and exposed on `EmFieldSystem.reflected` (`Fields.fs:550`): the complex ratio ρ = r_p / r_s yields tan(Ψ)·e^{iΔ}, so Ψ = atan(|ρ|) and Δ = arg(ρ). This file MUST NOT fork `Solvers.fs` or `FieldFunctions.fs` (§0 constraint 2); it consumes their outputs and MUST share the Ψ/Δ definition of Part F §F.5 (`psiDelta`) rather than re-deriving an independent one.

The two new functions MUST be surfaced as additional cases reachable by `FitTarget` (G.4) so ellipsometric targets compose identically to photometric ones. Because `FieldFunctions.fs:109` `OpticalFunction` is closed and §0 constraint 2 forbids forking it, this part MUST add `Psi` and `Delta` as a small net-new `EllipsometricFunction` DU local to `Ellipsometry.fs` with its own evaluator over `EmFieldSystem`, NOT by editing the engine's `OpticalFunction`. The completion of the Mueller path (`FieldFunctions.fs:93`) is owned by Part F §F.3 and MUST NOT be revived by this part — it is outside the fitting scope named in 010 §II.5.

### R-7 (G.7) Inverse fitting from measured R/T and Ψ,Δ [Standard]

This part MUST implement inverse fitting from measured data in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/InverseFit.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 §II.5. Measured photometric (R/T) and ellipsometric (Ψ, Δ) spectra MUST be loaded via FSharp.Data (the import library named in the Part A storage seam and 010 §III.2) from CSV/tab sources and converted to canonical SI sample points (wavelength in meters via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`) at the import boundary only.

Each measured spectral point MUST be turned into a `FitTarget` (G.4) whose `OpticalFunction`/`EllipsometricFunction` matches the measured quantity and whose desiredValue is the measured datum; the resulting `FitTarget list` MUST be handed to the G.5 local-refinement entry point. The regressable model parameters MUST be the G.3 design variables — thicknesses, dispersion coefficients (optical constants), and geometry — matching 010 §II.5 ("regress model parameters (thicknesses, optical constants, nonuniformity, roughness)"). Nonuniformity and roughness MUST be expressed, when in scope, as additional `DesignParameter` closures over the base system, NOT as new engine primitives; this part adds no roughness physics beyond what such a closure expresses. This file MUST NOT introduce a measurement-format registry or autodetection beyond the explicit CSV/tab path named here.

### R-8 (G.8) Fit-quality reporting [Standard]

This part MUST compute and expose fit-quality metrics in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/FitQuality.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 §II.5. From the `OptimizationResult.finalResiduals` (G.1) and the residual Jacobian at the solution, this part MUST compute χ²/MSE, parameter confidence intervals, and the parameter correlation matrix, and MUST retain the per-sample residuals for residual plots and fit-vs-measured overlay (010 §II.5).

The confidence intervals and correlation matrix MUST be derived from the covariance estimate (inverse of JᵀJ scaled by reduced χ²). The required real-matrix inverse/factorization MUST go through the Part A math seam `MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5` (this is engine-side linear algebra, NOT optimization, so ALGLIB MUST NOT be used here per §A.8); the cloned Math.NET routines reached via that seam are the primitive to call. The residual-plot and overlay data MUST be returned as plain arrays for the G.10 UI and the charting path (`plotComparison`, `Charting.fs:38`); this part MUST NOT render charts itself. A `FitReport` (new record) MUST aggregate χ²/MSE, the interval/correlation tables, and the residual arrays, and MUST be persistable as a `.binz` fit-history sidecar (§0 constraint 4; `serialize … BinaryZippedFormat`, `Core.fs:257`), NOT inside the canonical JSON project.

### R-9 (G.9) Needle/tunnelling synthesis and global optimization [Standard]

This part MUST implement synthesis methods in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/Synthesis.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 §II.5. **Needle optimization** MUST, at each iteration, evaluate the merit-function gradient with respect to inserting a vanishingly thin layer at each candidate depth in the films list of the base `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`), insert one `Layer` (`Media.fs:24`) of small thickness at the position that most decreases the merit function, then re-run local refinement (G.5) on the grown design — growing the layer count without bounding the parameter space (010 §II.5). **Tunnelling / gradual evolution** MUST perturb a converged design to escape local minima and re-refine, combined with needle insertion per 010 §II.5.

**Global optimization** MUST provide simulated annealing and a genetic/evolutionary algorithm for multimodal merit landscapes where refinement stalls (010 §II.5). These MUST be driven through the same G.1 `Residual` closure and MUST select the appropriate `OptimizationMethod`/ALGLIB routine through G.2 where one exists; the annealing/GA outer loop that ALGLIB does not provide MAY be implemented in this file as an explicit F# loop over the `Residual` closure, with each candidate evaluated by the G.4 merit assembly. This part MUST NOT add parallel-evaluation infrastructure, distributed execution, or a plugin system for synthesis strategies — only the two synthesis families and two global methods named in 010 §II.5.

### R-10 (G.10) Synthesis/Fit operator page, jobs, and result refresh

This part MUST add a top-level Synthesis/Fit page to the FuncUI MVU surface (`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj`, Part A assembly map) hosting the G.4 target editor, the G.3 parameter/bound table, the method selector (G.1 `OptimizationMethod`), and the G.8 fit report. Because this introduces an operator page and long-running cancellable jobs, this part MUST commit explicitly on the operator-facing UX checklist:

1. **Discoverability/nav entry** — the page MUST be reachable from the main navigation as a named "Synthesis / Fit" entry alongside the existing stack/chart pages.
2. **Progress granularity** — every optimizer run MUST report progress as iteration count and current χ²/MSE via a progress channel distinct from the G.1 interface (G.1 stays callback-free); the channel MUST update at each optimizer iteration. The shared background-job runner of Part J §J.10 hosts this run; this part supplies the per-iteration progress payload.
3. **Pre-confirmation gate vs one-click** — starting a fit MUST be one-click (non-destructive: it produces a candidate system, it does not overwrite saved files); ACCEPTING a fit result that replaces the working `OpticalSystem` MUST require an explicit confirm.
4. **Completion → results refresh** — on optimizer completion the refined system MUST be folded back via G.3 and the result charts MUST refresh through the existing `plotComparison` path (`Charting.fs:38`) showing fit-vs-measured overlay (G.8) without a manual reload.
5. **Opposing-action button UX + undo** — the page MUST provide a Cancel button that cooperatively stops the running optimizer (the G.5/G.9 loops MUST observe a cancellation flag) and a Revert action restoring the pre-fit working system; Cancel and Start MUST NOT be the same control.
6. **Committable file vs root .gitignore collisions** — `.binz` fit-history sidecars (G.8) and any exported fit reports MUST be written under the project's working folder and MUST be added to the repository root `.gitignore`, NOT committed; the canonical JSON project (which references them as sidecars, §0 constraint 4) is the committable artefact.

Long-running execution MUST run off the UI thread so the MVU `update` stays responsive; this part MUST NOT add a job-queue, retry, or scheduling abstraction beyond a single cancellable run at a time.

### R-11 (G.11) Validation against the Wolfram reference fits

This part MUST validate the ALGLIB `minlm` path against the Wolfram reference fits, per §A.8 ("Validate ALGLIB's `minlm` against the Wolfram reference fits"), in a new test file `Berreman/BerremanTests/OptimizationTests.fs` added to `BerremanTests.fsproj` (`Berreman.slnx:20`). The tests MUST encode, as fixed expected values, the converged parameters and final χ² from the ported Wolfram `FindMinimum`/`NonlinearModelFit` runs for at least one thin-film R/T refinement case and one ellipsometric Ψ/Δ case, and MUST assert that `LocalRefinement` (G.5) driving `LevenbergMarquardt` (G.2) reproduces them to a stated tolerance.

The tests MUST exercise the full path — `DesignParameter` mapping (G.3) → merit residual (G.4) → `optimize` (G.1) → ALGLIB adapter (G.2) — using the real `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`), NOT a stubbed forward model, so the validation covers the engine/optimizer seam end to end. A bounded-parameter case MUST assert that a fit started outside the physical range terminates inside the G.3 bounds (no negative thickness). These tests MUST NOT depend on the UI project.

## Non-requirements

- The engine solver, field model, and math seam are reused unchanged (binding constraint 2); ALGLIB is used for optimization ONLY and MUST NOT route engine linear algebra (G.2; §A.8).
- The Ψ/Δ derivation is shared with Part F §F.5 `psiDelta` (slice 006) and MUST NOT be forked (G.6); the Mueller-path completion (`FieldFunctions.fs:93`) is owned by Part F and MUST NOT be revived here.
- No new C# project; ALGLIB is a NuGet `PackageReference` (G.2; §0 constraint 1).
- The simplex (`NelderMead`) backend choice is deliberately undecided and MUST surface as `Failed "simplex backend unresolved"` until decided (G.2).
- The shared background-job runner (progress/cancel/timing harness) is owned by Part J §J.10 (slice 010); this part supplies the per-iteration progress payload only. The chart rendering path (`plotComparison` surfaced through ScottPlot) is owned by Part H (slice 008).
- Caching of forward evaluations, retry/backoff, optimizer-plugin discovery, config-knob proliferation, schema versioning of fit payloads, error-wrapping shims, parallel/distributed evaluation (§0 constraint 6; G.0/G.9).

